{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d7b34df6-5422-4146-90a5-48fba4f3706f","content":"## The Problem\n\n.NET MAUI's Android workload **bundles its own Microsoft OpenJDK 17**. When your `JAVA_HOME` points to a different JDK (Adoptium Temurin), the build uses mismatched Java tooling and fails.\n\n## The Fix\n\n**Option A — Let .NET use its bundled JDK (recommended):**\n\nUnset `JAVA_HOME` before building so the .NET Android SDK uses its own JDK:\n\n```bash\nunset JAVA_HOME\ndotnet build\n```\n\nTo make it permanent, remove the `JAVA_HOME` export from your `~/.zshrc` / `~/.bash_profile`.\n\n**Option B — Point to Microsoft's OpenJDK:**\n\nThe workload installs it at a path like:\n\n```\n/usr/local/share/dotnet/packs/Microsoft.Android.Sdk.Darwin/*/tools/jdk\n```\n\nSet `JAVA_HOME` to that path instead.\n\n**Option C — Override in your `.csproj`:**\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup Condition=\"$([MSBuild]::IsOSPlatform('osx'))\">\n  <JavaSdkDirectory>/usr/local/share/dotnet/packs/Microsoft.Android.Sdk.Darwin/35.0.x/tools/jdk</JavaSdkDirectory>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n**TL;DR:** Unset `JAVA_HOME` — .NET MAUI ships its own JDK and doesn't need yours.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"eac227b2-c4a9-40d4-8122-11eee0d605ea","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is having a .NET MAUI Android build failure related to Java. They have Adoptium Temurin JDK 17.0.12 installed. Let me think about what the common issue is here.\n\nThis is a well-known issue: .NET MAUI / Xamarin Android builds require a specific JDK. Starting with .NET 8, the Android SDK requires JDK 17, but there's a specific issue with **Adoptium Temurin** JDK on macOS.\n\nActually, let me think more carefully. The common issues with MAUI Android + Java are:\n\n1. **JDK version compatibility** — .NET 8+ Android requires JDK 17. They have 17, so that's fine.\n\n\n2. **JAVA_HOME path issue on macOS** — On macOS, Adoptium Temurin installs to a path like `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home`, and JAVA_HOME needs to point to the correct location.\n3. **The Microsoft OpenJDK vs Adoptium issue** — .NET MAUI recommends Microsoft's OpenJDK distribution. The Android SDK build tools may have issues with non-Microsoft JDKs.\n\nThe most common and well-known issue is that **.NET Android / MAUI expects the Microsoft OpenJDK** distribution specifically.  While other JDK 17 distributions can technically work, using Adoptium Temurin instead of the Microsoft OpenJDK that ships with the .NET Android workload often causes build failures. The likely culprit is that .NET 8/9 MAUI installs and expects Microsoft's OpenJDK 17 via the android workload, and when `JAVA_HOME` points to a different JDK like Adoptium Temurin, the .NET Android build system's `JavaSdkDirectory` configuration conflicts with it, leading to errors like `UnsupportedClassVersionError`, Gradle/d8/r8 failures, or `Could not determine java version` messages.\n\nThere's also a known issue with JDK 17.0.12 from Adoptium that specifically breaks Android builds. On macOS, .NET MAUI Android uses the Microsoft OpenJDK bundled with the workload, but when `JAVA_HOME` is set to Adoptium, the Gradle and Android build tools pick up the wrong JDK, causing the build to fail because the Android SDK expects its own bundled version.\n\nThe solution is to either unset `JAVA_HOME` entirely so .NET uses its bundled JDK, or point it directly to Microsoft's OpenJDK installation.","outputTokens":1315,"requestId":"3C28:8F118:D72675:10B3E2B:6A01299E"},"id":"7eb6a6f0-63c8-45d4-b6a6-737be0ad97e0","timestamp":"2026-05-11T00:58:35.128Z","parentId":"d6f5376c-563a-4f52-8c25-c1b65a14562e"}
